\f2\b 2. Socks in the Dark
\f3\b0 \
I have 20 socks in a drawer that are a mixture of black, brown, and white. I need to grab some matching pairs of socks out of the drawer, but the room is dark. \
\
First, I need to find one matching pair of socks without turning the lights on and grabbing the least amount of socks as possible. After that I have to find matching pairs of socks in each color without turning the lights on and grabbing the least amount of socks as possible.\
\
I need to determine the odds of grabbing matching pairs of socks; first, I\'92ll determine the probability of grabbing each type of sock. There are 5 pairs of black socks, 3 pairs of brown socks, and 2 pairs of white socks, making 10 pairs or 20 total socks. 10 of the 20 socks are black, 6 of 20 socks are white, and 4 of 20 socks are white. Therefore, I have a 50% of grabbing a black sock, a 30% chance of grabbing a brown sock, and a 20% chance of grabbing a white sock. Because socks don\'92t have a specific foot they must be on, any black sock will pair with another black, any brown sock will pair with another brown, and any white sock will pair with another white.\
 \
My first goal is to get a matching pair of socks in any color. Based on the statistics determined above, if I grab 4 socks and they are black, brown, and white I can grab one more sock and have at least two socks of the same color. \
\
To obtain a pair of socks in each color, I would pull 8 socks out of the drawer. If I grab 10 socks odds are 5 of them will be black, 3 of them will be brown, and 2 of them will be white. That would give me a matching pair of socks in each color.\
